{"title_page": "Matthew Harding", "text_new": "{{For|the American world traveler of the same name|Matt Harding}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name                 = Matthew Harding\n|image                = \n|image_size           = \n|caption              = \n|nationality          = \n|birth_name           = Matthew Charles Harding\n|birth_date           = {{birth date|df=y|1953|12|26}}\n|birth_place          = [[Haywards Heath]], [[Sussex]], England\n|death_date           = {{Death date and age|1996|10|22|1953|12|26|df=yes}}\n|death_place          = [[Middlewich]], [[Cheshire]], England\n|spouse               = Ruth Harding\n|children             = 3\n}}\n'''Matthew Charles Harding''' (26 December 1953 &ndash; 22 October 1996) was a British businessman, vice-chairman of [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea Football Club]] and a major financial supporter of [[New Labour]].\n\n==Early years and education==\nHarding was born in [[Haywards Heath]], [[Sussex]], the son of Paul Harding, an insurance executive. He attended [[Abingdon School]] in [[Abingdon-on-Thames]] from 1964 until 1971.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abingdon.org.uk/uploads/school/files/abingdonian/1965_January_V013_N004.pdf#page=21|title=Valete et Salvete|publisher=The Abingdonian}}</ref> He was a member of the badminton first team, for which he was awarded half-colours, in addition to being a cricket first XI player, captain of the colts cricket team and a member of the hockey second XI.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abingdon.org.uk/uploads/school/files/abingdonian/1971_February_V015_N004.pdf#page=24|title=Badminton|publisher=The Abingdonian}}</ref> Although he enjoyed the sport, he did not enjoy the school ethos, earning a single 'A' Level in Latin.\n\nIn June 1995, he was appointed a \"Steward\u201d of [[Abingdon School]] and presented the awards at \u201cLeavers\u2019 Day\u201d.  He also donated \u00a3500,000 towards the school\u2019s \u201cMercers Court\u201d, a new IT centre where one of the rooms was named \u201dThe Matthew Harding Careers Room\u201d in his honour after his particular interest in offering career\u2019s advice to the students.<ref name=\"Return to Abingdon\"> {{Cite book | last =Rudd | first =Alyson | title =Matthew Harding: Pursuing the Dream | year =1997 | publisher =Mainstream Publishing | isbn =1-85158-957-0 | page =42}}</ref>  He returned to the school just weeks before his death to speak to a small group of sixth formers about his road to success. \n\n==Career==\nHe left school and went to [[London]]. Through his father's friendship with Ted Benfield, he joined the insurance brokers [[Benfield Group|Benfield, Lovick & Rees]] and it was in the insurance industry that he made his fortune, starting out by making the tea and going on to be a director. By 1980, he had acquired a 32% stake in the company, becoming one of Britain's 100 richest men.\n\nHe donated \u00a31m to the Labour Party in 1996.<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/news/multi-millionaires-who-keep-blair-in-his-office-1352967.html</ref>\n\n==Chelsea FC==\n[[File:Chelsea 2 Bolton Wanderers 1 (15165243508).jpg|thumb|right|A banner at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] in 2014, in tribute to Harding. It reads \"Matthew Harding's Blue & White Army\"]]\nA lifelong fan of [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea Football Club]], Harding responded to Chelsea chairman [[Ken Bates]]' call for new investment in the club in 1993.   In October 1993, he was appointed as a [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea Football Club]] director.  He invested \u00a326.5&nbsp;million in the club, including \u00a37.5m towards construction of \"Matthew Harding Stand\", \u00a316.5m to buy the [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] freehold and transfer funds.<ref name=\"Chelsea director and investment\"> {{Cite book | last =Rudd | first =Alyson | title =Matthew Harding: Pursuing the Dream | year =1997 | publisher =Mainstream Publishing | isbn =1-85158-957-0 | page =94}}</ref>  Chelsea named one of the stands at Stamford Bridge the \"Matthew Harding Stand\".\n\n==Death and legacy==\nHarding died at the age of 42 in a helicopter accident in October 1996, while flying back from a Chelsea match at [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]], along with the pilot and three passengers, including journalist [[John Bauldie]]. The crash of the [[Eurocopter AS355 \u00c9cureuil 2]] aircraft took place at night and in poor weather, near [[Middlewich]], [[Cheshire]]. An investigation by the [[Air Accidents Investigation Branch]] found that the pilot did not have the experience or qualifications necessary to safely [[Instrument flight rules|pilot by instruments]] in such conditions.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/35069.stm | title=Pilot 'unable to control' Harding helicopter | publisher=[[BBC News]] | date=27 November 1997 | accessdate=26 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHis son Patrick Harding is now a semi-professional footballer who plays for [[Burgess Hill Town F.C.]]<ref>{{cite news |date=4 May 2014|title=Cuckfield Cosmos crowned winners of Matthew Harding Cup final|url=https://www.westsussextoday.co.uk/sport/football/cuckfield-cosmos-crowned-winners-of-matthew-harding-cup-final-1-6038885|work=West Sussex Gazette|access-date=16 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Old Abingdonians]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* ''Matthew Harding: Pursuing the Dream'' by [[Alyson Rudd]] Mainstream Publishing (16 Oct 1997) {{ISBN|1-85158-957-0}}\n* ''A Question of Honour'' by [[Lord Michael Levy]] Simon & Schuster (12 May 2008) {{ISBN|1-84737-315-1}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harding, Matthew}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Abingdon School]]\n[[Category:Chelsea F.C. chairmen and investors]]\n[[Category:English football chairmen and investors]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Victims of helicopter accidents or incidents]]\n[[Category:People from Haywards Heath]]\n[[Category:Victims of aviation accidents or incidents in England]]\n[[Category:20th-century English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) donors]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the American world traveler of the same name|Matt Harding}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name                 = Matthew Harding\n|image                = \n|image_size           = \n|caption              = \n|nationality          = \n|birth_name           = Matthew Charles Harding\n|birth_date           = {{birth date|df=y|1953|12|26}}\n|birth_place          = [[Haywards Heath]], [[Sussex]], England\n|death_date           = {{Death date and age|1996|10|22|1953|12|26|df=yes}}\n|death_place          = [[Middlewich]], [[Cheshire]], England\n|spouse               = Ruth Harding\n|children             = 3\n}}\n'''Matthew Charles Harding''' (26 December 1953 &ndash; 22 October 1996) was a British businessman, vice-chairman of [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea Football Club]] and a major financial supporter of [[New Labour]].\n\n==Early years and education==\nHarding was born in [[Haywards Heath]], [[Sussex]], the son of Paul Harding, an insurance executive. He attended [[Abingdon School]] in [[Abingdon-on-Thames]] from 1964 until 1971.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abingdon.org.uk/uploads/school/files/abingdonian/1965_January_V013_N004.pdf#page=21|title=Valete et Salvete|publisher=The Abingdonian}}</ref> He was a member of the badminton first team, for which he was awarded half-colours, in addition to being a cricket first XI player, captain of the colts cricket team and a member of the hockey second XI.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abingdon.org.uk/uploads/school/files/abingdonian/1971_February_V015_N004.pdf#page=24|title=Badminton|publisher=The Abingdonian}}</ref> Although he enjoyed the sport, he did not enjoy the school ethos, earning a single 'A' Level in Latin.\n\nIn June 1995, he was appointed a \"Steward\u201d of [[Abingdon School]] and presented the awards at \u201cLeavers\u2019 Day\u201d.  He also donated \u00a3500,000 towards the school\u2019s \u201cMercers Court\u201d, a new IT centre where one of the rooms was named \u201dThe Matthew Harding Careers Room\u201d in his honour after his particular interest in offering career\u2019s advice to the students.<ref name=\"Return to Abingdon\"> {{Cite book | last =Rudd | first =Alyson | title =Matthew Harding: Pursuing the Dream | year =1997 | publisher =Mainstream Publishing | isbn =1-85158-957-0 | page =42}}</ref>  He returned to the school just weeks before his death to speak to a small group of sixth formers about his road to success. \n\n==Career==\nHe left school and went to [[London]]. Through his father's friendship with Ted Benfield, he joined the insurance brokers [[Benfield Group|Benfield, Lovick & Rees]] and it was in the insurance industry that he made his fortune, starting out by making the tea and going on to be a director. By 1980, he had acquired a 32% stake in the company, becoming one of Britain's 100 richest men.\n\n==Chelsea FC==\n[[File:Chelsea 2 Bolton Wanderers 1 (15165243508).jpg|thumb|right|A banner at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] in 2014, in tribute to Harding. It reads \"Matthew Harding's Blue & White Army\"]]\nA lifelong fan of [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea Football Club]], Harding responded to Chelsea chairman [[Ken Bates]]' call for new investment in the club in 1993.   In October 1993, he was appointed as a [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea Football Club]] director.  He invested \u00a326.5&nbsp;million in the club, including \u00a37.5m towards construction of \"Matthew Harding Stand\", \u00a316.5m to buy the [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] freehold and transfer funds.<ref name=\"Chelsea director and investment\"> {{Cite book | last =Rudd | first =Alyson | title =Matthew Harding: Pursuing the Dream | year =1997 | publisher =Mainstream Publishing | isbn =1-85158-957-0 | page =94}}</ref>  Chelsea named one of the stands at Stamford Bridge the \"Matthew Harding Stand\".\n\n==Death and legacy==\nHarding died at the age of 42 in a helicopter accident in October 1996, while flying back from a Chelsea match at [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]], along with the pilot and three passengers, including journalist [[John Bauldie]]. The crash of the [[Eurocopter AS355 \u00c9cureuil 2]] aircraft took place at night and in poor weather, near [[Middlewich]], [[Cheshire]]. An investigation by the [[Air Accidents Investigation Branch]] found that the pilot did not have the experience or qualifications necessary to safely [[Instrument flight rules|pilot by instruments]] in such conditions.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/35069.stm | title=Pilot 'unable to control' Harding helicopter | publisher=[[BBC News]] | date=27 November 1997 | accessdate=26 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHis son Patrick Harding is now a semi-professional footballer who plays for [[Burgess Hill Town F.C.]]<ref>{{cite news |date=4 May 2014|title=Cuckfield Cosmos crowned winners of Matthew Harding Cup final|url=https://www.westsussextoday.co.uk/sport/football/cuckfield-cosmos-crowned-winners-of-matthew-harding-cup-final-1-6038885|work=West Sussex Gazette|access-date=16 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Old Abingdonians]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* ''Matthew Harding: Pursuing the Dream'' by [[Alyson Rudd]] Mainstream Publishing (16 Oct 1997) {{ISBN|1-85158-957-0}}\n* ''A Question of Honour'' by [[Lord Michael Levy]] Simon & Schuster (12 May 2008) {{ISBN|1-84737-315-1}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harding, Matthew}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Abingdon School]]\n[[Category:Chelsea F.C. chairmen and investors]]\n[[Category:English football chairmen and investors]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Ca